    <patterns>
      <pattern name="C# interface alias" location="Standard C# `using OldName = Namespace.NewName;` directive">
        Place the alias either in a shared `GlobalUsings.cs` (preferred for source-compat
        across the project) OR per-file in the small set of consumer files. Choose whichever
        matches the existing project convention; document the choice in task notes.
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="0" name="Context Check + Rigor Declaration">
      Output: "🔒 RIGOR LEVEL: FULL — interface rename impacting multiple consumers + downstream blocker for 6+ tasks". Read project CLAUDE.md + spec.md FR-06.
    </step>
    <step order="1" name="Review Progress">
      Read TASK-INDEX. Update `current-task.md` to task 006.
    </step>
    <step order="2" name="Gather Resources">
      Read inputs + knowledge. Capture baseline publish size. Use Grep to find ALL consumers of `IAnalysisToolHandler` across `src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/` + `tests/`.
    </step>
    <step order="3" name="Rename the Interface">
      Rename file `IAnalysisToolHandler.cs` → `IToolHandler.cs`. Rename type symbol. Update its namespace if needed.
    </step>
    <step order="4" name="Add Source-Compat Type Alias">
      Add `using IAnalysisToolHandler = Sprk.Bff.Api.Services.Ai.IToolHandler;` in `GlobalUsings.cs` (or equivalent) so existing handler files compile without per-file edits. Verify approach matches project convention.
    </step>
    <step order="5" name="Build + Test">
      `dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/` → 0 errors. `dotnet test tests/unit/Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests/` → all green. Confirm: all existing handlers + DI registrations resolve correctly.
    </step>
    <step order="6" name="Verify Publish Size">
      `dotnet publish -c Release` → measure delta vs baseline; report ≤+5 MB R6 budget.
    </step>
    <step order="7" name="Verify Acceptance Criteria">
